I am a new student at ACI, just started about a 3 weeks ago at the Tulare/Visali. I should of read these reviews before signing up to this school. The school is very unorganized there are to many students out in the yard and not that many instructors. The instructors are always joking around not doing anything, dont offer any help or guidance only reach out to you when you are driving and are about to crash and they dont talk politely they shout out you very unprofessional. When I first spoke with Joe the counselor, he made it sound like it was a well organized school, but it is just a front. <Name>Todd Lehrkind</Name><Pics>None<//Pics><rating>1<//rating>< review>
1 star is still to much for this school. I finished the welding program and there is no structure what so ever. One of the instructors is so strict he will either just flat out tell you to re-weld, get out calilers to measure, or make up his own rules about how you you need to prep your coupons or how you need to hold the electrodes. You are supposed to be there to learn not be criticized to the point you dont want to weld. He also will not let student use certain pieces of equipment that you need to learn, you then have to wait on him to come cut the metal for you at his own pace while you wait and are not welding.Your there to learn not be criticized by someone with no welding certifications or qualifications. The owners are a joke as well all they want is your money, they would rather open a new campus then invest into the equipment at the existing campuses. They go to auctions and get old equipment instead of getting new machines. The air extraction system sucks you leave school with metal in your nose and they dont provide equipment you need to properly fit up your metal, they just say you need to know how to do it without pipe clamps but dont have pipe clamps or dont show you any other methods do fit up your metal. When I got started no one showed me what to do they said this is how it's done and then went on to sit in the air conditioned class room while I basically taught my self how to weld in a 120 degree shop in the middle of summer. If you actually want to learn how to weld and get hands on training do not go here.<//review>

< Review>
I had a great experience with the Advanced Truck Driving School! Now the school is known as the Advanced Career Institute. I became unemployed in 2005. I had wanted to get my commercial license to drive trucks for a living. Through the WIA program at EDD that became possible. The folks at Advanced were very professional there and helped me get to my goal. "Getting my CDL". After 6 short weeks I had my CDL in hand. I graduated on a Friday and on Monday I was working! You can't beat that!  One thing that really impressed me was that when I was finding out about the school they were really interested in my background. I found out that this was because they wanted to make sure that I could get a job as a truck driver, and that I was qualified. That tells me that they were more interested in ME and not just the money. Thumbs up to Advanced!  I went to work for Werner Enterprises and eventually became a Trainer. Since then I worked for Knight Transportation and Dunns Sand in Visalia, Ca. and am still in the trucking industry. Just want to say Thanks Advanced!!< /Review>

< text>
We moved to Stockton recently and needed a new bed frame for our Avocado mattress. I looked up different furniture stores and chose this one based on it's reviews. I wasn't disappointed. Staff was helpful, knowledgeable, and friendly. They pointed us to quite a few options they had available, since we needed a frame that would support around 600lbs (it's a heavy mattress, and we're not lightweight people). This is a great community if you don't mind the loud neighbors at night.

Let's talk about pros first. The apartment management team is great, provides excellent services. Can't speak about the amenities since it has been closed after COVID breakout. Location is good as it's walkable to wholefoods and many restaurants.

The cons is that there are some people living in the community is really careless about others. We have neighbors upstairs running in the living room with large size dog in the middle of the night and neighbors shouting & partying after 10pm. Earplugs become our best friend as we have many restless night. I don't feel home here and there is never a quiet moment. During the day there is construction noise and keeping windows open is not an option if need to focus on work related stuff. Another thing to mention is that there are cockroaches in the apartment.

If you are not sensitive to noise level and can sleep through the night, I'd highly recommend the apartment as management team is nice and location is convenient.< /text>

< pictures>

< review>
We are about to vacate and I wanted to take the time to write a review. My family and I have lived in 4 different corporate apartment complexes in the last 12 years, and Avalon Morrison Park is my favorite. True, no home or apartment is perfect, but this one checks nearly all of the boxes.

The Highlights:

Great Community
The neighborhood is close to perfect. There are plenty of shops and restaurants in walking distance: Whole Foods, Ace Hardware, Recycle Book Store, and plenty of coffee shops, convenience stores and restaurants. There is literally a winery next to the entrance, Coterie, which has some of the best Pinot Noir I've ever tasted. We had a courtyard-facing townhouse, which means our little kids could play safely outside and we never had to worry about them, since the courtyard is gated. Add to that our chill neighbors, and we really felt safe and welcomed here - a valuable commodity in downtown San Jose, let me tell you.

Chill Staff
Carlos and Adrian, two amazing maintenance workers, have never let me down, despite my best efforts to wreck the apartment. Joking aside, the entire maintenance staff (don't know all their names) have always been great, and their willingness to continue doing a great job during Covid definitely earns my admiration. Likewise, the office staff Miguel, Shaima and Ricardo have been nothing but friendly and polite to me and my family. They even helped out my parents when they had to evacuate their home due to wildfires. It's nice to see an apartment community keep a good office staff - these roles tend to turn over pretty frequently at the other places I rented.

Solid Amenities
Everything got shut down in March due to Covid, which seriously sucks. They opened up the gym, pool, and barbecue areas, but the reservation system is...not great. But, when they were open full time, the Gym and pool were amazing. We got in shape last year because of how easy it was to get to the gym and work out, so I hope things go back to normal for residents soon. Other great amenities include plenty of underground parking, and a good package system, although I wish the mailboxes were in the same location.

The Downsides (nothing is perfect):

1. The apartment building construction on Julian and Stockton makes its presence known; although we were in a unit that was far away, I'd hate to be in a unit closer to that. Tons of dust and noise would make living nearer the construction unbearable.

2. We never had our car broken into, but we did have three bikes stolen from the bike room - a common occurrence, we later found out. After that I locked my remaining bike to the patio wall.

3. I paid the highest PG&E bills ever in this place. I don't know if it was because of the direction we faced (south), or the 3-floor layout, but I paid nearly twice as much per month on energy than I did in a single-floor apartment with close to the same square footage.

With all that said, this townhouse with a patio, and courtyard access, is probably the best "apartment" layout you'll find in San Jose, especially if you have kids. Having a pool, gym, and barbecues was nice when they were all more accessible before Covid. Now, they just seem like pointless value-adds that you'll end up paying higher rent for, but never use.<//review>

<user_name>EA McGuire</user_name>< user_id>
106244810269850531613</user_id>
<Date>1583350705845<//Date><Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
This place is awesome - I love living here.  The apartment is perfect but it's the people and experiences you have in an apartment complex who make or break it.  The front office staff - Victor, Miguel, and Shaima - are fantastic.

Here are examples:
I was in the office one day and commented that people occasionally turn a corner in the complex a little fast... and a few days later 5 mph signs showed up on both sides of that corner!

I locked myself out and they not only came up and let me in, but double checked the working of the lock and then followed up by calling and asking me if I had found my keys!  Also, one time Victor sat for a good half hour fiddling with a key I had dropped so that it worked again, and then another time when the battery on a key seemed a little weak they right away replaced it with a new one.

They walk packages up to your door if you forgot to pick them up from the Amazon Hub, rather than just letting Amazon take them back.

Beyond just being helpful, they are also genuinely nice.  When you go into the office, they don't just give you incredible service, they also chat in such a friendly way that you sort of forget why you came in the first place.  They are completely invested in their jobs.

I am probably forgetting at least a dozen other nice things they have done in my 8 months I have been here, but you get the idea.

Safety -
I have never once seen a non-resident on my floor.  Everyone is always just coming and going from their places.  Honestly I have forgotten to lock my door several times and wasn't worried when I got back.  I have never seen sketchy people inside the complex, ever.

Maintenance -
They mean it when they say they fix anything in 24 hours, and that said, the only maintenance requests I had to put in were a clogged sink and a broken doorbell, both of which they fixed right away and in a courteous professional way.

Residents -
I have lived in 5 different apartment complexes in 5 different cities and I have never once been in such a friendly building.  The guy across the hall offers to help you carry groceries or heavy stuff in.  People pet your dog and chat when they're out walking their dogs.  Nobody has messy balconies or front terraces.  There is a great mix of young professionals, small families, and elderly retired people.  It's super diverse - I have met people from Japan, Greece, Iran, India and many other places.  There are often a few people around the pool, in the gym, or at the BBQ area, but never too many.  It doesn't feel crowded but it doesn't feel deserted.

Events -
At first I was skeptical about the occasional events hosted in the BBQ area but then I brought my son to the pumpkin carving and it was adorable.  Cute kids, young couples.  Someone on my hall put the pumpkin they had carved outside her door.

Apartment -
Cute, super functional, and spotless when I moved in.  Easy to make it feel like a home.

In short - best apartment experience ever.</Review>

<userid>103281012250422971731</userid><Date>1507847585063<//Date>< Review>
We've been living in a townhome here for 18 months. Cleanliness is decent within the complex and most of what you request a fix for is dealt with within a day or two. It's a plus that most units have balconies or terraces. Good-sized, clean (and almost new) units. OK value for the money, but less so as rents increase year over year.

Good common spaces and amenities (pool could be a little warmer, but we're happy to have one). Rec room, gym and outdoor grill area are well-kept and clean. The staff are helpful when it comes to small tasks, but are somewhat unresponsive when it comes to issues like theft, complex cleanliness outside of the BBQ areas/clubhouse, and evident unit damages from faulty design + maintenance.

The little landscaping there is on site is well-kept, but for the area (and even the nearby Avalon on the Alameda) it is sorely lacking.< /Review>

< Text>
Avalon Morrison Park is a lovely place to live.  Centrally located to most major freeways but not close enough to hear any of the traffic noise. Great for using SJC airport if you are frequent traveler, less than a $10 Uber.

One of the other main reasons Avalon Morrison Park was such a great place to live was its excellent staff and management headed by its very own Natalie Stout. < user_id>
100396382172775092597< /user_id>
< Review>
Avalon Morrison Park is a great place to live. My wife and I have been residents for over a year and have no real complaints. Probably the best part about the community is the staff, and this seems to hold true for all of Avalon's properties (we've looked at a couple others and are always treated well!). For instance, Miguel will see us walking up from his desk inside the "fishbowl" leasing office and have our packages ready. He knows our names, apartment number, and even personal details that we've talked to him about. The cool thing is that this isn't the case just for us (even though I can't imagine that we're *not* his favorite residents), he knows everyone. There have been a couple others who have joined the team recently and they explicitly mentioned trying to get to know everyone. This is just a really great touch, and makes dealing with any issues super simple!

Some nitpicky things: the grills don't seem to be cleaned very often, trash is often overflowing at some of the public areas, and the pool heater seems to rarely be turned on (which was probably the most enticing amenity when we moved in).

As for maintenance, the team is awesome. We haven't really had a lot of issues (probably because the unit is brand new), but when we have, they're very responsive. We even put in a couple of requests for community things (i.e. timer for grills being shut off at the wrong time) and it was resolved the next day (after reporting it late at night).

The property itself is beautiful--lots of amenities, community happy hours, brand new gym, and cabanas by the pool. For San Jose, the location is great. It's close enough to walk to all of the downtown excitement (~1 mile to Santa Clara and First), but far enough that you're not in the middle of it all. The Alameda is becoming more built up, and best of all there's a brand new Whole Foods a 2 minute walk away (with a awesome bar!).

In closing, one of the best perks about living at an Avalon community is that they will let you transfer your lease to another property, even before your lease is up (with no charge as long as it's over 50 miles). If you're looking for a place to live, definitely put this one on your list of considerations.<//Review>

<text>We lived at AMP for about 2 years. The only reason we moved out was because I changed jobs in another city.

PLUSES:
+ Natalie and the staff are all SUPER nice and very responsive to problems. I think we only had 1 issue that wasn't solved in about 24 hours and it was because they had to order a part.
+ The apartments are all newly built and have great features.
+ SUPER dog friendly and there are a lot of dogs for your dog to play with
+ The outside grill areas are great for parties and met a lot of my neighbors that way

Minuses are few but I will list them.

MINUSES:
- expensive (Welcome to silicon valley)
- The city water is very "hard" and that makes your dishes and bathrooms "crusty". Also causes the water to be turned off every 2 months or so for "maintenance" which is really just descaling the pipes from buildup. Expect to go thru a lot of CLR
- They rent to college students who are pretty careless with their surroundings sometimes. Maintenance does a good job of keeping everything clean Monday thru Friday, but weekends can get a little trash-ridden.
- That part of the city has a lot of petty theft. The complex is no exception. The staff does a good job of using cameras to track down problem areas but assume anything not nailed down outside will get swiped.<//text>< user>

< review>
I've used this store before with no issues at all what so ever. My last time was absolutely horrible!

I tried to send a package internationally in May. Shipping was shy over $150. It went a town over, and ended up getting delivered to my house, a month later, with no information given. I gave the UPS store a call to get information. They had no info. The best they could do is make a claim for a refund. They told me that this takes at least 30 days to investigate.

A month of no word, I give them a call. Still investigating. 3 months go by. The manager of the ups escalates it and should receive an update in 5 business days. I call a week later, still no update. I wait another month. Nothing.

About two weeks ago, I finally managed to get an update. My claim was closed a month ago, and done with. No refund. UPS associate told me to email my number over, and that they would forward it to the owner to give me a call.

< Text>
I've used this store before with no issues at all what so ever. My last time was absolutely horrible!

I tried to send a package internationally in May. Shipping was shy over $150. It went a town over, and ended up getting delivered to my house, a month later, with no information given. I gave the UPS store a call to get information. They had no info. The best they could do is make a claim for a refund. They told me that this takes at least 30 days to investigate.

A month of no word, I give them a call. Still investigating. 3 months go by. The manager of the ups escalates it and should receive an update in 5 business days. I call a week later, still no update. I wait another month. Nothing.

About two weeks ago, I finally managed to get an update. My claim was closed a month ago, and done with. No refund. UPS associate told me to email my number over, and that they would forward it to the owner to give me a call.

It's been nearly 3 weeks since. No call. No resolution. I would strongly avoid this place. Multiple occasions they have hung up on me after having put me on hold for 20-30 minutes.</Text>

< Review>
When we moved to Torrance 16 years ago we checked out a couple of dentist offices. Another practice was interested in performing lots of dental work that was not covered by our insurance. Select Dental works with our insurance to provide the best care, and takes the time to explain the reasons for any procedure that goes beyond our coverage.

The dentists and hygienists all do an excellent job and have a great "chair-side manner." The front desk is friendly and efficient. Since they deal with most every type of insurance be sure you have a basic idea of what insurance you have and how it works. Give 'em a hand and they'll do right by you.

The team at Select Dental had been fighting their old office building for years. Recently they move a couple blocks down the street to what is basically a new facility. Very high tech, and now they have decent parking, too!

Dad, mom, the kids and even grandma go to Select Dental for our orthodontic and dentistry needs.</Review>

<rating>1< /rating><Review>SO DISAPPOINTED!

I took my Model 3 into the Costa Mesa Service Center to fix a rattle that Burbank tried to fix twice.

After pulling up, I wandered around for 10 min., not knowing where to check in, until I was finally told to wait in my car.

After another 20 minutes of waiting in my car, Dan came to my window.¬† I explained the rattling and he brought over a technician, who confirmed the rattling after a test drive.

Then I talked to Dan again and asked if he could check the brake fluid and let me know if it needs to be changed and fix the rattle.¬† He drew up the paperwork and it's¬†$195¬†for the fluid flush and¬†$97.50¬†to fix the rattle.¬† I asked, "Isn't the rattle covered by warranty?"¬† He says, "Well we just put a cost for labor down in case we find out it was due to outside forces like rats nibbling on wires or something."¬† "But isn't this a carry-over from what the Burbank Service Center couldn't fix?" I asked.¬† Then he started a word salad about the California Lemon Law and how if an issue isn't fixed by the fourth time you have the right to return the vehicle.¬† That's why they put a labor cost on the estimate.¬† (I am assuming so it looks like a new problem instead of an existing one.)¬† "So you put down a cost to get around that law?" I asked.¬† His next answer was like a politician deflecting a question, about how they are the hub for Tesla repairs and they get hundreds of cars a week, and they have experienced people there.¬† I had to stop him from going on with his non-answer and said, "When I took it into Burbank, they had this zeroed out both times."¬† He explained then that he always tried to side with the customer when it comes to warranty issues.¬† He wants his customers to have a good experience and because it's only¬†$100¬†he has no problem eating the cost.

It had been 2 hours at this point, so I signed and left.

After two days, my car was ready and because I had to work, my wife to picked up my car.

Her experience was the same as mine.¬† She parked and wandered around until someone told her to wait.  After 30 minutes of waiting, someone came out and asked, "Who's next?"¬† She looked around at the other people waiting, and since no one knew who was next, she stood up and said, "I think it's me."

She told me after that they charged her $300 and I asked for the receipt.¬† She said they didn't give her one.¬† I then tried to look at the estimate they had emailed me to sign, but when I clicked the "review and sign" link, I was greeted with a "This document has already been signed," message, with no option to download.¬†¬†I hadn't received any invoices via email, or via the Tesla app either.¬† I called the Service Center but there was no answer, so I left a message.

The next day I received a text from Dan saying I'll get a survey and if he didn't get 5 stars, to contact him.

I replied that I never received notification I would be charged and would like to see the receipt.

Dan sends me the invoice and I see I was charged for the fluid flush and the rattling.

I text him back:

"So I was charged for the rattling? That wasn't a warranty issue?"

He responds:

"Yes. You were charged¬†$97.50¬†for the rattle. This was not a warranty repair. Rattles and squeaks are only covered for the first 6 months of ownership."

I respond:

"You told me I would only be charged if it was due to outside forces like rats. You mentioned nothing about 6 months. Was what you told me when I signed the document untrue?"

After 2 days with no response, I text:

"Hey Dan, I'm looking for a response to my last question."

He has yet to respond.

The Costa Mesa Service Center seems unorganized, uncaring, and it feels like your typical shady car shop.

This was my wife's first experience with Tesla.¬† After months of trying to convince her to trade in her Mercedes SUV for a Model Y, she flatly rejected it saying, "I don't want to have to take my car to that shop.¬† Tesla's service is so bad."</Review>< pictures>

Instead of several hours, I was told to wait several days.  I could not wait for loan car, said I would take care of my self.  The customer service man said I would have some credit for it.

After several days, I had to call to ask if the jobs have been done.

Eventually, when I got the car back, it was extremely dirty, they said almost no problems was found, no credit was give for me to have loan car.

Some one was using the Google in my car to entertain some thing.

The customer service man was nice, but too busy.

It seemed the coordination is to bad, no team work, no discipline there.  The staff  seemed was not well trained, either skills nor attitude to do their job.

Tesla is good car in general, but the service for car problem is unbelievable inefficient in this center.

My car have some of the same  problems and new problems, but I am scared with the service and hesitate to call for service.

I hope the management of the service center will be reviewed and will be a focus of the company.

Need to have better trained and supervision of staff over there to be sure all if them working honestly, professionally, and efficiency.

I like the functions of Tesla.  But the services, as I experienced there, were so inefficient and unpleasure.

I wish I will be able to refer more clients to Tesla as I wished, but with these kind of services, I dare not.

Hoang<//review>

<Name>Cliff Fornwalt</Name>< pics>
None<//pics>
< Text>
This is one of the busier Tesla Service centers. They are often overwhelmed, and that has been consistently the case since I've been going here since 2013.  They often promise to follow up things, or to add something to your repair ticket, but they frequently drop things.  You constantly have to remind them to do things.  If you have several minor issues you have scheduled an appointment for in the future, then have to go in for an emergency, they'll just take care of the emergency issue and make you come back a second time. They have zero flexibility in their schedule.  People are nice, but the customer service people aren't very knowledgeable. If you are a car enthusiast, or just someone who knows a little more than average about cars, your questions will certainly throw their customer service people into nervous shuffling mode.  In addition, they clearly have only worked at Tesla, since they're thrown off by simple questions you typically ask your mechanic, like "can I see the old part you replaced?" Forget it. You're never gonna see that part.  You'll probably also never get an explanation about what that part does, or what went wrong with it, or how sure they are that it was the root cause, and won't fail again soon due to some other problem.  Each time you have an issue, they act like it's the first time they've ever seen that issue, so they can't answer any questions about it.  That's clearly not current, since Teslas have less than half the moving parts of a regular car... There can only be so many things that go wrong... You'd expect them to be experts after only a short while.

They do their best to provide good customer service with a smile, but they don't have this business down the way experienced car dealerships and independent mechanics do.

All the same, your car will get fixed eventually, and almost everything is done free under warranty service, so my complaints are really just from an engineer who wants to know the details, as I've always done with every car I've ever owned.</Text>

< text>
A great spot by the Monterey Bay Aquarium to grab a meal after exploring the aquarium itself or Cannery Row! The menu is diverse and hearty! The blacked ahi sandwich is delicious! A huge piece of tuna with Cajun seasonings sandwiched between ciabatta buns, the slaw complements it well. The entire thing will leave you dreaming for more.   Duke's Luau Pork left a little to be desired.  It felt more like a teriyaki pulled pork dish, still! it wasn't bad.  Just not what I was expecting.<//text>

< user>
106133545040155724196<//user>
< Text>
My daughter chose this place for our dinner tonight.  We went in hungry and left stuffed!  Delicious food with large entree portions.

Started out with the abalone calamari and it was delicious.  The seared ahi wontons were yummy.  These were appetizers/pupus.  Both great choices.

The entrees were absolutely delicious and the portions HUGE!  I had the Ahi Tuna Bowl and it came in a large bowl, along with my daughters Kingston crab curry. What a unique flavor- Yum!  My son had the jerk pork.  Perfectly cooked with the right texture.  The Kalbi ribs my other daughter had was flavorful and very soft, not hard like some places.  To top off the entrees, my wife had the Fish soup and it was HUGE!  I swear after we passed the bowl around with all the members of the family, there was still some leftover that would probably last another meals worth.

We finished off the evening with the most awesome pies.  Do not leave without having a piece of the lilikoi Rita Pie on a Graham cracker.  That pretty much finished off my evening to the last piece.  Our waiter Marcus was very attentive and polite and the ladies that helped out were polite as well.  We're coming back again here for sure in the future!!</Text>

< text>
It is a great get a away for the kids. Need some peace to be able to hear your own thoughts?  Want to put them to bed tired and willing?  This park has every conceivable contraption, swing, slide, and activity for them to let off all that pent up energy. It is very busy during the day, so go early. < text>
This fun little Hawaiian grill in Monterey can make me feel like I'm back in Honolulu.  I ordered Duke's luau platter,  which did make me fondly remember the luau at the Hale Koa. The only thing missing was poi. The pulled pork and pineapple was great!
My husband ordered the Kingston curried crab. It was a bit spicy,  but that crab was so good.
I've eaten at Hula's when we lived here before,  but it was my husband's first time here. He enjoyed it, so we'll probably be back.<//text>

Probably the best restaurant in the area. Definitely the best I've tried in Monterey. Prices are a touch high but still worth your $. Good variety of drinks and the menu is large. < Review>
Loved the atmosphere of this place, almost felt like as if I was on an Hawaiian island! Came by on a Saturday night, they are very busy, so be prepared to wait at least 20 to 30 minutes. They do have a bar where you can first grab some drinks or there is a speak easy bar right next door that is owned by them as well.

<resp>None<//resp><Text>I do not give a 5 star rating often. Hula's is an approachable understated exceptionally fun and flavorful experience. Immediately greeted by Lynnette my wife and I were seated by the window allowing us to see all the excitement of the bar and the servers. We arrived for happy hour and were encouraged to order off that menu. Everything is $6 and the flavors will blow your mind. Had seared ahi tuna, kona wings, abalone calamari and grilled avocado. All were bursting with unique flavors and left me wanting to try another dish. Drinks were spot on, not to light and fantastically balanced. Amazingly none of the cocktails were too sweet, all made with natural fruit juices and allowed to impart genuine flavors of the tropics. The atmosphere was relaxed and fun and the server made us feel welcome and appreciated; even making suggestions and listening to my gluten free rant. < text>
The food was fantastic, the staff was great, and the outdoor seating area was perfect for lunch with the dogs.

That being said, the only reason I gave this 4 stars is because I specifically called ahead, twice, to confirm that they had room outside for us (we had the dogs) and to ask if we needed a reservation to hold the outdoor spot. We were told they werent busy and we didn't need a reservation.

It took us less than 5 minutes to get there and upon arrival we were told we had to wait because they didn't have a space open outside.

The rest of the experience was fantastic. Both of our meals were amazing and they even cooked chicken breast for the dogs.

Overall I would go back as it might have been a random bad incident.< /text>

<review>I landed here synchronistically. When I walked in I knew it was my kind of restaurant because of its ambience. It has a good feel, or what they call Good Vibe Tribe.

Had I known there was a place out back to sit I would've chosen that, but I discovered their gorgeous heated outdoor patio after I took a seat at the bar, which was very cool and played surf flicks on tv rather than other sports.

The original server gave me a recommendation upon asking and that is the Kingston Crab Curry pictured here. It well beyond meet my expectations. It's a meal in itself, and another server recommended I try some extra spice (garlic red chili sauce) which was like icing on the cake.

I tried a few different beers, and had I been in the mood for whiskey or sake (or any other spirit) they seemed to have a sufficient variety.

Definitely a must try. Fresh seafood. Tasty beyond belief.</review>< pics>

<UserId.>106196871769362082373< /UserId.><Name>Thomas G</Name><Time>1480403603433< /Time>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< Text>
Even though it was a cold, Monterey night, I and my companions were warm and cozy on the patio. We sat for hours drinking delicious cocktails and eating tasty appetizers without worrying about breaking the bank thanks to the happy hour prices on those things. Propane heating thingies kept us toasty, aided by the courtesy blankets provided in a bin. Our server was friendly, on point, and made great recommendations. I'm used to going to (and enjoying_ the Hula's in Santa Cruz, but the Monterey location is a cut above.<//Text>

< review>
I love this place. Everyone is super nice. If TraderJoes had a restaurant it would be this place. I have tried:
ahi tacos, spicy, crispy, big portion. Amazing
Jawaiian jerk pork platter, spicy and AMAZING
Godzilla tots. Try them
Curry tofu bowl, so so good
Jawaiian chicken plate, also amazing.
Steak sandwich: this will change your life

Get the steak sandwich. I am pretty sure it breaks some physical laws it is so good. My life is now in two distinct parts, the time before I tried the steak sandwich and the time after. Evidently the kolbi ribs are even better. I am a little afraid to try them.

Get the spicy edamame. De-licious.

I have now, literally, gone back and lowered the review for other places because Hula's continues to raise the bar. Perfect 7/5 ;-)

They have a vegetarian menu and a gluten free menu.

Tasty drinks also.

Go. Go now.</review>

This place is absolutely fantastic. The service is friendly and attentive, the drinks are well made and well priced (especially during happy hour) and the food is absolutely delicious. <user>112168701981401767810</user>< username>
N Clever< /username>
<Time>1529005028180< /Time><rate>1</rate>< review>
We were very excited to visit this restaurant for the name alone. They don't take reservations. They were very full but seated us with almost no wait. the decor is very cute and tropical kitschy. Our waitress  was snooty , unfriendly and had a blank stare the few times she actually came to our table. We ordered drinks and appetizers first.  Our drinks came but the appetizers never showed up. When they served our entrees the server tried to remove the dishes meant for our appetizers. When I mention we still had not received the appetizers,  the server walked away. A little while later another guy came to remove the appetizer plates again. This time I sarcastically mentioned that we never received our appetizers .  He then suggested to cancel our appetizers. At that point I was very irritated due to the service and the people next to us, so I said that he should just do what he thought was best for us. A little while after that our waitress finally returned to our table and said she put in the order for appetizers.  They eventually showed up after our meal was finished. No apologies although they did comp the appetizers .

FYI, the seating is very close together so the conversation at the next table will become your conversation, whether you want it to or not. Be forewarn. Once we were seated another group of four women were seated at the table next to us. They were ear piercingly loud and their entire conversation for over an hour consisted of dildos, vibrators, masturbation, and how to avoid having to give it to their husbands or how to get it from strangers without obligation. We also learned that one of the women's husband was a vegan and they were in a fight so she was going to order the ribs because that was going to torture him when she got home. At one point it got quiet. After a few minutes one of the women noted how quiet it was. The other woman noted that it was because they were being quiet. And they all broke out in ear drum rupturing laughter and resumed loud talk about wearing out the batteries of their vibrators. None of which was enjoyable as a parent of two young children having to listen to them. Please people, be aware that there are other human beings around and some are very young. The walk back to our car became awkward when my 8 year asked what is a dildo and what is masturbation?</review>

< Review>
The food here must have been designed by an artist who sees protein as their canvas and complementary herbal matrimonies as their pallette. Sounds cheesy, but it‚Äôs true. The dishes are great! On top of that, our waitress (cute short-haired blonde lady on a Monday) was so passionate about the food and our satisfaction that I would have left happy even if my meal tasted terrible. Luckily it didn‚Äôt though.

Have the edamame, even if spicy scares you, and if spicy does scare you, dip it in the black pepper. I promise it adds the perfect amount of smoke and, ironically, salt.</Review>

< Text>
Love Duke's Kalua Pork. I always order it with the fried plantains. Scrumptious. And the best mai tai I've ever had!  Fabulous food, friendly staff, awesome decor filled with vintage Hawaiiana that makes you feel as if you're in the islands. (Note: if it's a super hot day - -  which is rare for Monterey - - be warned that there is NO air conditioning. Plenty of fans, though.) Quaint outside patio.  A MUST if you're in Monterey or in Santa Cruz.  Hula's, please open in Santa Barbara!</Text>
